> what is the purpose of the vendors folder?

● The vendors folder (under /assets/vendors/) is for third-party libraries and frameworks that come with their own
  static assets (CSS, JS, fonts, images). It keeps external dependencies organized and separate from your custom
  theme/plugin code.

  Common Examples:

  In Themes:

  /theme/falcon/assets/vendors/
  ├── bootstrap/              # Bootstrap CSS framework
  │   ├── bootstrap.min.css
  │   └── bootstrap.min.js
  ├── fontawesome/           # Font Awesome icons
  │   ├── all.min.css
  │   └── webfonts/
  ├── jquery/                # jQuery library
  │   └── jquery.min.js
  ├── swiper/                # Swiper slider
  │   ├── swiper.min.css
  │   └── swiper.min.js
  └── chart.js/              # Chart.js library
      └── chart.min.js

  In Plugins:

  /plugins/myplugin/assets/vendors/
  ├── datatables/            # DataTables for admin tables
  │   ├── datatables.min.css
  │   └── datatables.min.js
  ├── select2/               # Select2 dropdown library
  │   ├── select2.min.css
  │   └── select2.min.js
  └── moment/                # Moment.js for date handling
      └── moment.min.js

  Benefits:

  1. Clear Separation: Distinguishes third-party code from custom code
  2. Easy Updates: Can update entire vendor library by replacing its folder
  3. License Tracking: Keep vendor licenses with their code
  4. Dependency Management: Easy to see what external libraries are used
  5. No Mixing: Prevents accidentally modifying vendor code

  Alternative Approaches:

  Some projects use CDNs instead of local vendor files, but having them local ensures:
  - Works offline/intranet
  - No external dependencies
  - Consistent versions
  - Better performance (no external DNS/SSL lookups)

  The vendors folder is essentially the static assets equivalent of Composer's /vendor/ directory for PHP
  dependencies.

